Notebook[{

Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["\<\
An Algorithm for the Placement of a Self-Balancing Prehensile Tail on a \
Leaning Mass\
\>", "Title",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.992418899646987*^9, 3.99241890259415*^9}, {
  3.992420680749268*^9, 3.9924207250340967`*^9}, {3.992439966659012*^9, 
  3.992439971739094*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3b4ad047-fa97-464f-8aeb-\
cd553dce18cc"],

Cell["\<\
Prehensile tails are tails which are extremely mobile, grasp objects, and \
provide support and stability to organisms such as primates, chameleons, and \
seahorses. Recently, robotics researchers have studied prehensile tails for \
applications in three dimensional body rotation movements and adding balance \
to quadrupeds and real-world elderly citizens. However, constructing these \
robotic prehensile tails often involves complex calculations, tuning, and \
specifications for motors. To prevent these, I created an algorithm to \
compute the exact positioning for a prehensile tail which has any given \
number of joints, masses, sizes to balance out a counterweight of any given \
height and mass.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.99253491701397*^9, 3.992534923571272*^9}, {
  3.992534961932871*^9, 
  3.9925349620918818`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"422e58d5-5de6-4839-8b6f-\
e8c10a8c4ce2"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Introduction", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.992443330238624*^9, 
  3.992443336737669*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"913d55a0-652d-4ba7-af7a-\
f7b31dc48b4b"],

Cell["blah blah blah", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.992443338678629*^9, 
  3.9924433402969913`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e6255813-4355-435f-b32d-\
d510d3b27df2"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Model V1 - Self-Balancing Tail with Variable Length", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.929354612578005*^9, 3.929354616192994*^9}, {
  3.929355210549653*^9, 3.9293552190879917`*^9}, {3.9918429510719347`*^9, 
  3.991842958992612*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"067356c3-28ca-4144-be02-\
7957e03610f3"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Before changing the angle of the tail or adding more joints, we need to \
understand how balance works. In physics, balance is achieved by having a net \
torque of zero in our system. In this case, our system is defined as the \
following: a center of mass for the tail offset by a distance and a center of \
mass for the head offset by a distance and height. The \
tail\[CloseCurlyQuote]s center of mass is the midpoint because it is a normal \
object while the head is a point mass. For all calculations, we will use SI \
units.\n",
